<h2>Required components</h2>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Executive Summary</strong> (1 page or 60 sec) — headlines only: what's the problem, what does the science say, what's the top recommendation.</li>
  <li><strong>Background</strong> (~1 page) — the underlying climate physics at GCC-appropriate level. Plain-language explanation of the greenhouse effect, projected warming, regional context for Chennai.</li>
  <li><strong>Evidence + Projected Impacts</strong> (~1.5 pages) — current state of the challenge + 20-year and 50-year projections using IPCC + Chennai-local data.</li>
  <li><strong>Recommendations</strong> (~0.5 page) — 3-5 specific, actionable, evidence-anchored actions for GCC. <em>Avoid</em> "raise awareness" recommendations — they don't count.</li>
  <li><strong>Sources</strong> — at least 3 reputable sources, including at least 1 IPCC reference. AI sources allowed with full AI Documentation.</li>
  <li><strong>OPVL evaluations + AI Documentation Template</strong> (separate submission) — required if AI was used at any stage.</li>
  <li><strong>Policy Panel defense</strong> — 4-min pitch + 3-min Q&A in Block 12.</li>
</ol>

<h2>What you'll be scored on</h2>
<p>The Chennai Climate Brief does triple duty: it assesses unit content (climate physics, IPCC science, regional projections, adaptation/mitigation distinction), it exercises <a href="/foundations/opvl-framework/">OPVL</a> on IPCC + government + AI sources, and it sharpens the policy-audience writing the year-arc has been building toward.</p>
<p><strong>Grade weighting</strong>: Brief 70% · Policy Panel 15% · Formative work (Blocks 1-9 activities, OPVL practice, peer feedback) 15%.</p>

<div class="callout warn">
  <div class="callout-title">📌 Three gates worth naming up front</div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Recommendations specificity is a T/T gate.</strong> If your 3-5 recommendations are vague ("raise awareness," "study the problem"), T/T caps at 3-4. Specific, actionable, evidence-anchored recommendations is the move.</li>
    <li><strong>Policy-brief voice is a C gate.</strong> Same trap as U2 — students writing academic-paper voice instead of audience-appropriate policy voice cap C at 5-6.</li>
    <li><strong>AI Documentation is a K/U gate.</strong> Same as U0 / U1 / U2. If AI was used and the Template is missing or trivial, K/U caps at 3-4.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

